sentences: Toña la Negra was born Antonia del Carmen Peregrino Álvarez on 2 November 1912 in La Huaca, a neighborhood of Veracruz, Veracruz.
Her father, Timoteo Peregrino Reyes (born c. 1857), played guitar and was a founding member of a guild of local port workers.
Her mother, Daría Álvarez Campos (born c. 1867), sang at family gatherings.
Toña began her career in the 1920s singing tangos as the lead singer of the Trío Peregrino-Uzcanga.
In 1932, she traveled to Mexico City and met songwriter and composer Agustín Lara.
She first recorded these songs and many others for Peerless Records in the 1940s.
In February 1953, her single "Como golondrinas" peaked at number 2 on Cashbox's Mexico's Top Ten Tunes chart.
She went on to record numerous hit singles and also several studio albums, including Caleidoscopio musical con Toña la Negra (1958), Noche criolla, vol.
II (1961), and La sensación jarocha, vol.
She recorded two songs with the Sonora Matancera in 1974.
They had three sons, Ramón (b. 1932), Guillermo (b. 1933), and Ernesto (1935–1979), and separated in 1945.

sentences: Antonia del Carmen Peregrino Álvarez (2 November 1912 – 19 November 1982), known by her stage name Toña la Negra (Toña the Black Woman), was a Mexican singer and actress of partial Haitian ancestry, known for her interpretation of boleros and canciones written by Agustín Lara.
Toña's paternal grandfather, Severo Peregrino, was from Port-au-Prince, Haiti and had immigrated to Mexico in the 19th century.
She began to record for the RCA Victor label in the late 1940s.
On Wednesday, 17 November 1982, she was admitted to a hospital in Mexico City because of cardiovascular problems.
That following Friday, 19 November, at the age of 70, Toña la Negra died of a heart attack.
